messages.content: 9-1-1, what's your emergency?
750 South, 650 West, apartment 154.
In Provo?
Yes.
750 South, 650 West, Unit 154.
Yes.
Is it at the Boulder?
Yes.
A phone number for you in case we get disconnected?
Do you need police or paramedics there?
I'm not sure. My friend called and basically told me she was going to kill herself, and I think she probably will.
Can you tell me her name?
It's Yvette Kimber, Y-V-E-T-T-E K-I-M-B-E-R.
How long ago did she call you?
Just right before I called you.
Do you know if she's taken anything?
I don't.
She called me at 8:59.
We're going to get some help over there. Do you know if she's alone?
Yes, I believe she's alone. I called her daughter, and her daughter's on her way over there, too.
Did she tell you how she was planning on doing this?
She said, I wanted to tell you goodbye, and I remember Skittles. I call her Skittles.
Okay, and you actually spoke to her, it was not a text message, correct?
I talked to her.
Alright, we have an officer headed that way. Did she have any weapons in the house that we need to be aware of?
I don't know. I'm in Santaquin; she's in Provo.
How old is she?
I think she's around 45. I'm not sure.
Has she been depressed recently?
Her boyfriend broke up with her today. And she has a long history of depression.
Do you know if she's tried to commit suicide in the past?
I've heard that she's tried to overdose before, but I've only met her last year.
What's her phone number?
Um, let me look it up.
Did you tell her you were going to be calling the police?
No, I didn't have time to. She hung up on me.
Alright, like I said, we do have an officer headed that way. Do you want them to make contact with you at all or just check her welfare?
I would like somebody to call me back and let me know what's going on.
Do you think she'd be upset if the police were to call her or show up?
I don't know because I don't think she'd answer to Whitney, her daughter.
Alright, thanks for calling. I appreciate it.
Bye.
9-1-1, what's your emergency?
Fire.
What's the address?
750 South, 650 West, parking lot number six.
750 South, 650 West, parking lot number six?
Yes, it's the Boulders.
Is the phone number you're calling from...
Pardon me?
Your phone number?
What city?
Do you need police or paramedics at the Boulders?
Uh, you may want to send paramedics just in case.
What's going on?
The fire is spreading.
What's on fire?
The apartment building.
Okay. Let me dispatch the fire department. Hold on. Don't hang up.
I won't.
It's on the outside now. The windows are exploding.
The paramedics are on the way. Are you outside the apartment right now?
No, but I need to go to my car. You may be better. Go across and get those people out of the apartment. We're trying to get everybody outside.
Is everybody out of the building?
We're trying to get them out now. We're yelling to get everybody out.
Okay. How many apartments are on fire?
Right now, one, but it's spreading.
Is anybody injured?
Not yet, but there's one or two people trapped upstairs.
Is someone trapped upstairs?
I see one person trapped upstairs trying to get out the window.
One person's trying to get out of the window?
Yes, ma'am.
We do have the fire department on the way. I'll tell you exactly what to do next. Are flames visible?
Yes, they're very visible. It's spreading all over the place.
And this is a large apartment building, correct?
It's building 28.
Building 28?
Yes, building 28, lot 6. It's spreading to the next building.
It's spreading to the next building?
Yes, ma'am. It's spreading to the next apartment, across the way from the fire.
We do have several fire units on the way. Can you tell me if the person made it out of the window?
Yes, I saw the person make it out of the window. There's another one trying to get out.
Is anybody stuck in the building right now?
Right now, I don't see anyone stuck.
We do have the fire department on the way. What's your name, sir?
<name>
Alright, thanks for calling.
Thank you.
Bye.
